    "text": "The paper defines memory-to-plan translation as a specific algorithm that reconstructs world states from possibly overwritten memory, not as a new class of problem.",
    "topic": "definitional status of translation"
  },
  {
    "text": "Partial observability alone does not necessitate memory-to-plan translation; agents can act reactively or from belief states without converting memory traces into plans.",
    "topic": "condition under which translation is needed"
  },
  {
    "text": "Overwritten world states (i.e., non-monotonic state changes) are the specific trigger for the translation mechanism described in the paper, making it a response to a particular sub-challenge of partial observability.",
    "topic": "triggering condition for translation"
  },
  {
    "text": "The paper presents memory-to-plan translation as a solution subcomponent that addresses, rather than constitutes, the foundational problems of partial observability and overwritten states.",
    "topic": "role as solution vs problem"
  }
]
